// Procedure Reference Data
export const PROC_DATA={
"General IM / Hospital Medicine":{
  "Peripheral IV Placement":{indication:"Medication administration, fluid resuscitation, blood draws; US-guided PIV for difficult access",sites:["Forearm veins (cephalic, basilic, median cubital)","Hand veins (dorsal venous network)","External jugular (emergent)"],steps:["Apply tourniquet proximal to site","Select vein — straight, non-branching, non-valvular segment","Clean with alcohol/chlorhexidine","Insert catheter bevel-up at 10-30° angle","Advance on flash of blood, thread catheter, remove needle","Flush with saline, secure with transparent dressing"],pearls:"US-guided PIV for difficult access (DIVA score ≥4): use high-frequency linear probe, tourniquet, identify vein in short axis, advance under real-time guidance. Long catheters (2.5-inch, 18-20G) for US-guided (deeper veins). Midline catheters (8-20cm) for 2-4 week access without central line risks.",usTip:"Probe: high-frequency LINEAR. Apply tourniquet, then scan in short axis (transverse) to identify a compressible, non-pulsatile vessel ≥4mm diameter. Distinguish vein from artery: veins are compressible, non-pulsatile, and irregular in shape. Use a longer catheter (2.5-inch) for deeper veins identified on US. Track the needle tip in real-time — keep it centered on the vein in short axis, or switch to long axis to visualize the entire needle shaft entering the vessel."},
  "Arterial Blood Gas (ABG) Sampling":{indication:"Assess oxygenation, ventilation, acid-base status; preferred over VBG when precise PaO2 needed",sites:["Radial artery (1st choice)","Femoral artery","Brachial artery (less preferred)"],steps:["Modified Allen test if radial","Palpate pulse, prep with alcohol","Pre-heparinized ABG syringe","Insert needle at 30-45° (radial) or 90° (femoral)","Advance until pulsatile blood flash","Collect 1-3mL, remove, hold pressure ≥5 min","Remove air bubbles, place on ice, send immediately"],pearls:"VBG can substitute for pH and PCO2 (within 0.03 pH units and 5mmHg) but NOT for PaO2. Hold pressure 5min (10min if anticoagulated). Pulse oximetry unreliable in CO poisoning, methemoglobinemia, severe anemia — need ABG."},
  "Foley Catheter Placement":{indication:"Acute urinary retention, accurate I/O monitoring in critical illness, perioperative, urologic surgery",sites:["Urethral (standard)","Suprapubic (surgical — if urethral not possible)"],steps:["Consent, position patient (frog-leg for female, supine for male)","Sterile prep with betadine/chlorhexidine (entire periurethral area)","Drape with sterile field","Inject 10-15mL lidocaine jelly into urethra (male)","Lubricate catheter tip generously","Male: hold penis upright at 90°, advance catheter to hub; Female: spread labia, identify meatus, advance 5-7cm","Inflate balloon with 10mL sterile water ONLY after urine return","Connect to drainage bag, secure to thigh","Document residual volume"],pearls:"If resistance in male: try larger catheter (coude tip if prostatic), gentle steady pressure. NEVER force — risk of urethral injury/false passage. Remove as soon as clinically possible (CAUTI risk increases daily). CAUTI bundle: avoid unnecessary placement, daily assessment for removal, aseptic insertion, closed drainage system."},
  "Nasogastric / Dobhoff Tube Placement":{indication:"NGT: decompression (obstruction/ileus), gastric lavage; Dobhoff: enteral feeding when unable to eat",sites:["Nostril → stomach (NGT) or post-pyloric (Dobhoff)"],steps:["Measure NEX distance (nose→ear→xiphoid)","Lubricate, insert along nasal floor","Patient flexes chin and swallows while advancing","Confirm: aspirate (pH ≤5.5), XR (gold standard)","Dobhoff: may need prokinetic (erythromycin/metoclopramide) or fluoroscopy for post-pyloric placement"],pearls:"Salem sump (double-lumen) for decompression; Dobhoff (weighted, single-lumen) for feeding. CI: basilar skull fracture (use orogastric). Never auscultation alone for confirmation. Post-pyloric feeding reduces aspiration risk in critically ill."},
  "Arthrocentesis & Joint Injection":{indication:"Diagnostic: acute monoarthritis (rule out septic joint, crystal arthropathy), joint effusion; Therapeutic: steroid injection, drainage",sites:["Knee (most common — suprapatellar or inferolateral approach)","Shoulder (posterior or lateral approach)","Ankle, wrist, MCP, elbow, hip (US-guided for deep joints)"],steps:["Consent; identify landmarks (or US guidance)","Sterile prep and drape","Local anesthesia (ethyl chloride spray or lidocaine wheal)","Insert needle into joint space, aspirate fluid","Send: cell count+diff, crystal analysis (polarized microscopy), gram stain, culture","For injection: after aspirating, inject steroid (triamcinolone 40mg large joint, 10-20mg small) ± lidocaine"],pearls:"Synovial fluid analysis: Normal WBC<200; Non-inflammatory<2000; Inflammatory 2000-50000; Septic >50000 (usually >90% PMN). Gout: negatively birefringent needles. Pseudogout: weakly positive birefringent rhomboids. NEVER inject through cellulitis. Septic joint is an emergency — orthopedic consult for washout.",usTip:"Probe: high-frequency LINEAR for most joints. US improves success rate and is strongly recommended for hip, shoulder, and small joints. For the knee: identify the suprapatellar recess in long axis — effusion appears as anechoic fluid distending the recess. For the shoulder: posterior approach with US identifies the glenohumeral joint space between the humeral head and labrum. US confirms needle tip is within the joint space and not in surrounding soft tissue."}
},
"Pulmonary & Critical Care":{
  "Endotracheal Intubation (RSI)":{indication:"Airway protection (GCS ≤8), respiratory failure (hypoxic or hypercarbic failing noninvasive support), anticipated clinical deterioration, inability to protect airway (massive hematemesis, angioedema, burns)",sites:["Orotracheal (standard — most common)","Nasotracheal (awake, spontaneous breathing — facial trauma with intact nasal passage)","Fiberoptic (predicted difficult airway, awake intubation, cervical spine precautions)"],steps:["Assess airway difficulty: LEMON criteria (Look externally, Evaluate 3-3-2, Mallampati score, Obstruction, Neck mobility) — have a failed airway plan BEFORE starting","Pre-oxygenate with 100% FiO2 for 3-5 minutes via NRB or BVM with PEEP valve; add apneic oxygenation (nasal cannula at 15 L/min left in place during intubation attempt)","Prepare and confirm all equipment: ETT (7.0-7.5 for women, 7.5-8.0 for men), stylet shaped into hockey-stick, video laryngoscope (preferred over direct), 10mL syringe for cuff, bougie, suction (Yankauer), BVM connected to O2, backup LMA/supraglottic airway, end-tidal CO2 detector","Position patient in sniffing position (head elevated, neck extended, ear-to-sternal-notch alignment) — ramp obese patients with towels/blankets under shoulders and head","Administer induction agent: etomidate 0.3 mg/kg IV (hemodynamically neutral) OR ketamine 1.5 mg/kg IV (maintains respiratory drive, bronchodilator) OR propofol 1.5-2.5 mg/kg IV (avoid in hypotension)","Administer paralytic: succinylcholine 1.5 mg/kg IV (onset 45-60 sec, duration 6-10 min) OR rocuronium 1.2 mg/kg IV (onset 60-90 sec, duration 45-60 min) — sugammadex available for reversal of rocuronium","Perform laryngoscopy: insert blade into right side of mouth, sweep tongue left, advance to vallecula (curved blade) or lift epiglottis directly (straight blade), visualize vocal cords — grade view using Cormack-Lehane classification","Pass ETT through vocal cords under direct visualization; advance until cuff is 2-3 cm past the cords; remove stylet","Inflate cuff with 5-10 mL air until no audible leak with positive pressure ventilation","Confirm placement: end-tidal CO2 waveform (GOLD STANDARD — must see sustained waveform for ≥6 breaths), auscultate bilateral breath sounds and epigastrium, note depth at teeth/lip (21-23 cm women, 23-25 cm men)","Secure ETT with commercial holder or tape; obtain CXR to confirm tip position 3-5 cm above the carina","Have push-dose epinephrine ready (10 mcg/mL): post-intubation hypotension is common due to loss of sympathetic drive, positive pressure ventilation reducing preload, and medication effects"],pearls:"ETCO2 waveform is the GOLD STANDARD for confirming tracheal placement — a colorimetric detector alone is insufficient in cardiac arrest (low CO2 production). Failed airway algorithm: if first attempt fails → reposition, use bougie, try different blade → second attempt fails → place supraglottic airway (LMA) → if cannot ventilate/cannot intubate → surgical cricothyroidotomy. Max 3 laryngoscopy attempts before declaring failed airway. Video laryngoscopy improves first-pass success by ~15% over direct (use as default when available). Succinylcholine contraindicated in hyperkalemia, burns >48h, crush injuries, neuromuscular disease, malignant hyperthermia history — use rocuronium instead. Ketamine is preferred induction agent in hypotension, reactive airway disease, and status epilepticus. Post-intubation sedation: start propofol or midazolam + fentanyl drip immediately after securing the tube."},
  "Cricothyroidotomy (Surgical Airway)":{indication:"Cannot-intubate, cannot-oxygenate (CICO) emergency — failed intubation AND failed supraglottic airway with desaturation; severe maxillofacial trauma precluding oral/nasal intubation; massive upper airway obstruction (angioedema, tumor, foreign body) not amenable to intubation",sites:["Cricothyroid membrane — palpable soft depression between thyroid cartilage (superiorly) and cricoid cartilage (inferiorly) in the anterior midline neck"],steps:["Identify the cricothyroid membrane by palpation: stabilize the larynx with non-dominant hand, palpate the thyroid cartilage notch, slide finger inferiorly to the soft depression before the cricoid ring","Prep the neck rapidly with antiseptic (do not delay in CICO emergency)","Make a vertical skin incision (3-4 cm) over the cricothyroid membrane through skin and subcutaneous tissue (vertical incision reduces risk of vascular injury)","Palpate the membrane through the incision; make a horizontal stab incision through the cricothyroid membrane itself","Insert a tracheal hook or the scalpel handle to maintain the opening; widen the incision by rotating the scalpel handle 90° or using a bougie as a guide","Place a cuffed tracheostomy tube (6.0 or smaller) or a cuffed ETT (6.0) through the membrane opening into the trachea; if using a bougie, railroad the tube over the bougie","Inflate the cuff, connect to BVM, ventilate, and confirm placement with end-tidal CO2 waveform and bilateral breath sounds","Secure the tube and obtain CXR"],pearls:"This is a LIFE-SAVING procedure of last resort — speed is critical. The scalpel-bougie-tube technique is fastest and recommended by the Difficult Airway Society and NAP4 audit. Needle cricothyroidotomy (14G catheter) is a temporizing measure only — provides inadequate ventilation in adults and should be converted to a surgical airway. The cricothyroid membrane is avascular in the midline — bleeding is usually from skin incision and is manageable. Complications include false passage (posterior tracheal wall injury), subcutaneous emphysema, bleeding, subglottic stenosis (long-term). Convert to formal tracheostomy within 24-72 hours in a controlled setting. In pediatric patients (<8-10 years), needle cricothyroidotomy with jet ventilation is preferred over surgical cricothyroidotomy due to risk of subglottic injury to the developing airway."},
  "Percutaneous Tracheostomy":{indication:"Prolonged mechanical ventilation (typically >14d), failed extubation, upper airway obstruction, pulmonary toilet",sites:["Between 1st and 3rd tracheal rings (typically 2nd-3rd)"],steps:["Consent; performed at bedside in ICU under bronchoscopic guidance","Position: neck extension (shoulder roll)","Sterile prep, local anesthesia","Bronchoscopy through ETT for visualization","Horizontal skin incision between cricoid and sternal notch","Needle access to trachea between rings under bronchoscopic guidance (transillumination)","Seldinger technique: wire → serial dilation → tracheostomy tube placement","Confirm: ETCO2, bronchoscopy, CXR"],pearls:"Timing: typically day 10-14 of MV (earlier if anticipated prolonged course). Percutaneous (Ciaglia) vs surgical — similar outcomes. Avoid if: coagulopathy, neck mass, high ventilator requirements, difficult anatomy. Decannulation: assess with capping trials + cuff leak test. Trach emergencies: if displaced <7 days, do NOT reinsert blindly (tract not mature) — orotracheal intubation instead."},
  "Thoracentesis":{indication:"New/undiagnosed pleural effusion, symptomatic large effusion, empyema",sites:["Posterior approach 1-2 ICS below effusion (never below 8th ICS)","US-guided MANDATORY"],steps:["US: confirm effusion ≥2-3cm, mark site","Sitting upright, leaning forward","Sterile prep, lidocaine (walk needle over superior rib edge)","Insert catheter, aspirating continuously","Aspirate diagnostic (50mL) or therapeutic (≤1500mL)","Send: cell count, LDH, protein, glucose, pH, gram stain, culture, cytology","Light's criteria for exudate vs transudate"],pearls:"Max 1-1.5L per session. Light's criteria: exudate if ANY of protein ratio >0.5, LDH ratio >0.6, LDH >2/3 ULN. Misclassifies ~25% diuretic-treated transudates → use albumin gradient >1.2. Post-XR only if air aspirated or symptoms.",usTip:"Probe: curvilinear or phased array. Patient sitting upright — scan posterior thorax. Identify diaphragm and effusion (anechoic space above diaphragm). Measure deepest pocket — need ≥1.5cm for safe entry. Mark the site at the rib interspace where fluid is deepest, noting the superior rib edge to avoid the neurovascular bundle. Color Doppler can help differentiate consolidated lung from effusion. SHM position statement recommends US guidance for ALL thoracenteses (reduces pneumothorax from ~10% to <1%)."},
  "Chest Tube (Tube Thoracostomy) & Pigtail Catheter":{indication:"Pneumothorax (large/symptomatic/tension/ventilated), hemothorax, empyema, malignant effusion for pleurodesis",sites:["Safe triangle: 4th-5th ICS, anterior to mid-axillary line"],steps:["Position: supine, arm abducted behind head","Sterile prep, generous lidocaine","1-2cm incision, blunt dissection OVER rib","Pop through pleura, finger sweep","Insert tube (28-32 Fr hemothorax; 14-24 Fr PTX/effusion) or small-bore pigtail (14 Fr) via Seldinger","Connect to drainage (Pleur-evac) at -20 cmH2O","CXR to confirm"],pearls:"Pigtail catheter (14 Fr, Seldinger) increasingly used for PTX and simple effusions (less painful, similar efficacy). Massive hemothorax: >1500mL initial or >200mL/hr×2-4h → thoracotomy. Tension PTX: needle decompress FIRST then tube. NEVER clamp tube draining PTX."},
  "Bronchoscopy (Diagnostic & Therapeutic)":{indication:"Diagnostic: BAL, biopsy (endobronchial/transbronchial), airway inspection, hemoptysis localization. Therapeutic: foreign body removal, mucus plugging, stenting, tumor debulking",sites:["Transoral through ETT or direct oral/nasal"],steps:["Topical anesthesia + sedation","Systematic inspection of airways","BAL: wedge in affected segment, instill 100-300mL saline, aspirate (>30% return)","Biopsy as indicated (forceps, needle, cryo)","Advanced: EBUS for mediastinal LN sampling; EMN/robotic for peripheral lesions"],pearls:"EBUS (endobronchial US): real-time guided LN sampling (staging lung CA, sarcoidosis). Radial EBUS: peripheral lesion localization. Robotic bronchoscopy (Monarch/Ion): reaches peripheral lesions. Cryobiopsy: larger tissue samples, less crush artifact. Therapeutic: APC, laser, cryotherapy for endobronchial lesions; stent placement for malignant airway obstruction."},
  "Prone Positioning":{indication:"Moderate-severe ARDS (P/F <150 despite optimized ventilation and PEEP)",sites:["Patient turned face-down on ventilator"],steps:["Multidisciplinary team (RT, nurses, MD)","Pre-prone checklist: secure ETT, lines, drains; eye protection; head-of-bed electrodes","Coordinated turn onto abdomen (minimum 5 people)","Position: swimmer's position, arms alternated q2h","Maintain ≥16 hours per session","Monitor for complications during prone: ETT displacement, pressure injuries, hemodynamic changes","Turn supine for procedures, assessments, or after P/F improvement"],pearls:"PROSEVA trial: ↓28-day mortality in moderate-severe ARDS (16 vs 33%). Must prone early (<36h of ARDS) and for ≥16h sessions. Contraindicated: unstable spine, open abdomen, elevated ICP. Awake proning (non-intubated) used in COVID — limited evidence but may delay intubation."},
  "Pleurodesis & Indwelling Pleural Catheter":{indication:"Recurrent malignant pleural effusion, recurrent pneumothorax",sites:["Via chest tube (chemical pleurodesis) or tunneled catheter (PleurX)"],steps:["Chemical pleurodesis: talc (most effective) via chest tube or VATS","PleurX catheter: tunneled subcutaneously, patient drains at home q48h","Pleurodesis occurs spontaneously with PleurX over weeks-months (50% auto-pleurodesis)"],pearls:"Talc pleurodesis: most effective (>90% success) but requires hospitalization and chest tube. PleurX: outpatient management, preserves lung expansion, useful if trapped lung. Choice depends on prognosis, lung expansion, patient preference. AMPLE-2 trial: no difference in dyspnea between talc vs IPC."}
},
"Cardiology":{
  "Echocardiography (TTE/TEE)":{indication:"TTE: new HF, murmur, dyspnea, post-MI, valve assessment. TEE: endocarditis (vegetation), intracardiac thrombus, pre-cardioversion (LAA thrombus), intraoperative",sites:["TTE: parasternal, apical, subcostal, suprasternal views","TEE: transesophageal — probe in esophagus"],steps:["TTE: patient left lateral decubitus, systematic views (PLAX, PSAX, A4C, A2C, subcostal, IVC)","TEE: NPO ≥6h, topical pharyngeal anesthesia, moderate sedation, bite block, advance probe"],pearls:"TTE: 1st-line for most cardiac imaging. Assess LV/RV function, valves, pericardium, IVC. TEE: superior for valves (especially mitral/prosthetic), LAA thrombus, endocarditis vegetations, aortic pathology. Contrast echo: agitated saline to detect PFO/ASD (bubble study). Strain imaging: GLS for subtle LV dysfunction (chemotherapy, infiltrative disease)."},
  "Pericardiocentesis":{indication:"Cardiac tamponade (Beck's triad: hypotension, JVD, muffled heart sounds), large symptomatic pericardial effusion causing hemodynamic compromise, diagnostic sampling (suspected infectious, malignant, or autoimmune pericarditis)",sites:["Subxiphoid approach (classic — most common, US-guided)","Apical approach (parasternal or apical — US-guided, sometimes preferred for anterior effusions)"],steps:["Obtain bedside echocardiography (POCUS or formal) to confirm effusion location, size, and identify the largest fluid pocket closest to the skin surface","Position patient at 30-45° upright (promotes gravitational pooling of fluid anteriorly/inferiorly)","Attach patient to continuous cardiac monitoring and pulse oximetry; have crash cart and defibrillator at bedside","Sterile prep and drape the subxiphoid or apical region; infiltrate local anesthesia (lidocaine) generously along the planned needle trajectory","Subxiphoid approach: insert an 18G spinal needle or pericardiocentesis needle 1-2 cm inferior to the left xiphosternal junction, directed toward the left shoulder at a 15-30° angle from the skin","Advance the needle slowly under real-time ultrasound guidance, aspirating continuously — enter the pericardial space when fluid freely aspirates","Confirm pericardial (not cardiac chamber) position: inject agitated saline through the needle — US should show bubbles appearing in the pericardial space, NOT within a cardiac chamber","Once position confirmed, use Seldinger technique: advance guidewire through needle → dilate → place pigtail drainage catheter (6-8 Fr) over wire into pericardial space","Aspirate fluid — even 20-50 mL removal can produce dramatic hemodynamic improvement in tamponade","Send fluid for: cell count, protein, LDH, glucose, gram stain, culture, cytology, and specific markers as clinically indicated (ADA for TB, tumor markers)","Secure catheter and connect to drainage bag; reassess with echocardiography to confirm reduced effusion; monitor output","Remove catheter when drainage is <25-50 mL per 24 hours (typically 24-72 hours)"],pearls:"Cardiac tamponade is a CLINICAL diagnosis — do not delay drainage for formal echo if patient is hemodynamically unstable. Pulsus paradoxus (>10 mmHg drop in systolic BP with inspiration) supports the diagnosis. Echo findings of tamponade: RA collapse in systole, RV diastolic collapse, IVC plethora, respiratory variation in mitral/tricuspid inflow. Always use US guidance — blind pericardiocentesis has a 20% complication rate vs <2% with US. Hemorrhagic pericardial fluid does NOT clot (unlike blood from inadvertent cardiac puncture, which will clot). Complications: cardiac perforation/laceration, pneumothorax, arrhythmia, coronary artery injury, hepatic injury. In traumatic tamponade, pericardiocentesis is a bridge to emergent thoracotomy — definitive treatment is surgical.",usTip:"Probe: phased array (cardiac). Subxiphoid view is best for identifying pericardial effusion and guiding needle entry. Identify the largest fluid pocket and measure distance from skin to fluid. Advance needle under real-time US guidance toward the effusion. Agitated saline injection through the needle confirms pericardial (not pleural) position — bubbles should be visible in the pericardial space. In emergent tamponade, even a small aspiration (20-50mL) can dramatically improve hemodynamics."},
  "Cardioversion (Synchronized) & Defibrillation":{indication:"Synchronized cardioversion: hemodynamically unstable SVT, atrial fibrillation/flutter, monomorphic VT with pulse. Defibrillation: ventricular fibrillation (VF), pulseless ventricular tachycardia (pVT). Elective cardioversion: AF/flutter with plan for rhythm control",sites:["Anteroposterior pad placement preferred (right parasternal + left posterior/infrascapular)","Anterolateral (right infraclavicular + left lateral chest wall at apex) — acceptable alternative"],steps:["Confirm the rhythm on monitor and determine if synchronized cardioversion or unsynchronized defibrillation is indicated","For elective cardioversion: ensure patient has been anticoagulated for ≥3 weeks OR obtain TEE to rule out left atrial appendage (LAA) thrombus; continue anticoagulation for ≥4 weeks post-cardioversion","Ensure IV access, continuous monitoring, and resuscitation equipment at bedside including suction, airway supplies, and crash cart","Apply defibrillator pads in anteroposterior position (preferred) — right parasternal at 2nd intercostal space and left infrascapular posteriorly","For synchronized cardioversion: PRESS THE SYNC BUTTON and confirm sync markers are tracking R waves on the monitor (sync must be re-selected after each shock on most devices)","Administer procedural sedation: propofol 0.5-1 mg/kg IV, etomidate 0.15-0.3 mg/kg IV, or midazolam 2-5 mg IV — ensure adequate sedation depth before shocking","Select energy: AF start at 200J biphasic (120-200J); atrial flutter/SVT start at 50-100J biphasic; monomorphic VT start at 100J biphasic. For defibrillation (VF/pVT): maximum energy from the first shock (200J biphasic)","Announce 'Charging — I am clear, you are clear, everyone is clear,' visually confirm all personnel are clear of the patient and bed","Deliver shock — the device will fire on the next detected R wave (synchronized) or immediately (defibrillation)","Immediately assess rhythm and hemodynamics post-shock; if unsuccessful, increase energy and repeat (escalating doses)","If synchronized shock produces VF: immediately switch to defibrillation mode (unsynchronized) and shock at maximum energy","Post-cardioversion: monitor for at least 1-2 hours, repeat ECG, resume/start anticoagulation, assess for skin burns at pad sites"],pearls:"SYNC mode for ALL rhythms with a pulse — synchronization delivers the shock on the R wave to avoid the vulnerable period (T wave), which could trigger VF. DEFIBRILLATION (unsynchronized) ONLY for VF and pulseless VT — there are no R waves to sync to. If synchronized cardioversion converts a rhythm to VF, immediately switch to unsynchronized defibrillation. AF >48 hours duration (or unknown duration): must rule out LAA thrombus with TEE or ensure ≥3 weeks therapeutic anticoagulation before cardioversion — risk of embolic stroke. Anteroposterior pad placement delivers more current through the heart and has higher cardioversion success than anterolateral. Biphasic waveform is more effective than monophasic at lower energy levels. Post-cardioversion anticoagulation: continue for minimum 4 weeks regardless of rhythm outcome (stunned atrium takes time to recover mechanical function)."},
  "Coronary Angiography & PCI":{indication:"STEMI (emergent), high-risk NSTEMI, stable angina failing medical therapy, positive stress test with high-risk features",sites:["Radial (preferred — fewer complications) or femoral artery access"],steps:["Arterial access (radial or femoral)","Catheter advancement to coronary ostia","Contrast injection for angiographic visualization","Identify stenosis, assess with FFR/iFR if intermediate","PCI: wire across lesion → balloon angioplasty → stent deployment (DES preferred)","IVUS/OCT for stent optimization if needed"],pearls:"Radial preferred (less bleeding — MATRIX/RIVAL trials). DES > BMS (less restenosis, requires DAPT). FFR ≤0.80 or iFR ≤0.89 indicates hemodynamically significant stenosis. STEMI: door-to-balloon <90 min. ISCHEMIA trial: initial invasive strategy did NOT reduce events in stable CAD with moderate-severe ischemia. — ABBREVIATION GLOSSARY — PCI: Percutaneous Coronary Intervention (catheter-based treatment of coronary artery disease). STEMI: ST-Elevation Myocardial Infarction. NSTEMI: Non-ST-Elevation Myocardial Infarction. FFR: Fractional Flow Reserve (pressure wire measurement across a stenosis during maximal hyperemia — ≤0.80 is significant). iFR: Instantaneous Wave-Free Ratio (resting pressure measurement — ≤0.89 is significant; no adenosine needed). IVUS: Intravascular Ultrasound (catheter-based US imaging inside the coronary artery to assess plaque burden, vessel size, and stent expansion). OCT: Optical Coherence Tomography (high-resolution intravascular imaging using light — superior resolution to IVUS for stent apposition, edge dissection, and thin-cap fibroatheroma). DES: Drug-Eluting Stent (coated with antiproliferative drug to prevent restenosis — requires DAPT). BMS: Bare-Metal Stent (no drug coating — higher restenosis rate, shorter DAPT). DAPT: Dual Antiplatelet Therapy (aspirin + P2Y12 inhibitor such as clopidogrel, prasugrel, or ticagrelor). CAD: Coronary Artery Disease. LAD: Left Anterior Descending artery. LCx: Left Circumflex artery. RCA: Right Coronary Artery. LMCA: Left Main Coronary Artery. CABG: Coronary Artery Bypass Grafting (surgical revascularization — preferred over PCI for left main disease or multivessel CAD with diabetes per SYNTAX trial)."},
  "Electrophysiology Procedures":{indication:"EP study: arrhythmia diagnosis; Ablation: AF, flutter, AVNRT, VT; Device implant: pacemaker, ICD, CRT",sites:["Femoral vein access (EP catheters)","Subclavian/axillary vein (device leads)"],steps:["EP study: diagnostic catheters placed in heart chambers","Map electrical activation and identify arrhythmia mechanism","Ablation: radiofrequency or cryoablation at target site","Device implant: subcutaneous pocket, leads advanced to RA/RV/CS"],pearls:"AF ablation: pulmonary vein isolation (PVI) — CABANA/CASTLE-AF trials. Pacemaker indications: symptomatic bradycardia, Mobitz II, CHB. ICD: primary prevention (EF≤35%+NYHA II-III, 40d post-MI), secondary prevention (survived VT/VF arrest). CRT: LBBB≥150ms + EF≤35% + NYHA II-IV. Leadless pacemakers (Micra): single-chamber, RV-only."},
  "Temporary Transvenous Pacing":{indication:"Hemodynamically unstable bradycardia unresponsive to atropine and chronotropic agents, symptomatic high-grade AV block (Mobitz type II, complete heart block), bradycardia-dependent ventricular tachycardia, bridge to permanent pacemaker implantation, prophylactic placement before procedures in patients with high-risk conduction disease",sites:["Right internal jugular vein (preferred — straightest path to RV)","Left subclavian vein (good alternative)","Femoral vein (easy access but higher infection risk, patient must remain supine)"],steps:["If hemodynamically unstable: initiate transcutaneous pacing immediately as a bridge (apply pads, set rate 60-80 bpm, increase current until electrical capture, then confirm mechanical capture with pulse)","Obtain central venous access using Seldinger technique via IJ, subclavian, or femoral vein — use a sheath introducer (6-7 Fr) rather than a standard central line","Under sterile conditions, advance the balloon-tipped pacing catheter (typically 5-6 Fr bipolar) through the introducer sheath","If fluoroscopy available: advance catheter under fluoroscopic guidance into the right atrium, across the tricuspid valve, and into the right ventricular apex","If no fluoroscopy (bedside/emergent): inflate the balloon, connect the distal (tip) electrode to the V1 lead of the ECG, and advance — monitor the intracardiac ECG waveform: large P waves in RA → injury current (ST elevation) at RV contact indicates correct position","Connect the external pulse generator: distal (tip) electrode to the negative terminal, proximal (ring) electrode to the positive terminal","Set initial parameters: rate 60-80 bpm, output 5 mA, sensitivity at demand mode","Determine the capture threshold: decrease output gradually until loss of capture, then set output at 2-3× the threshold (typically 1-2 mA threshold, set at 3-5 mA)","Determine the sensing threshold: decrease sensitivity until failure to sense, then set sensitivity at half the threshold value (more sensitive)","Secure the catheter at the insertion site, confirm position with CXR, and apply sterile dressing","Continuously monitor for capture (1:1 pacing spike followed by wide QRS) and hemodynamic response"],pearls:"Transcutaneous pacing is a BRIDGE only — it is painful (requires sedation/analgesia), unreliable for sustained use, and should be converted to transvenous pacing as soon as possible. Atropine 0.5 mg IV (max 3 mg) is first-line for symptomatic bradycardia but is INEFFECTIVE in Mobitz II and complete heart block (these are infranodal blocks). Right bundle branch block + left anterior fascicular block (bifascicular block) in the setting of acute MI is a high-risk pattern — consider prophylactic pacing. Complications of transvenous pacing: RV perforation (most serious), arrhythmias during placement (VT/VF — have defibrillator ready), pneumothorax, catheter dislodgement, infection, tricuspid regurgitation. Always verify mechanical capture — electrical capture on the monitor does not guarantee the heart is contracting (check pulse and blood pressure). Isoproterenol 2-10 mcg/min or dopamine 5-20 mcg/kg/min can be used as a temporizing chronotropic bridge while awaiting transvenous pacer placement."}
},
"Gastroenterology":{
  "EGD (Esophagogastroduodenoscopy)":{indication:"UGIB (within 12-24h), dysphagia, refractory GERD, Barrett surveillance, variceal screening in cirrhosis, PEG placement, foreign body removal, biopsy",sites:["Transoral: esophagus → stomach → duodenum"],steps:["NPO ≥6-8h, IV PPI if ulcer bleed suspected","Erythromycin 250mg IV 30min prior (improves visualization)","Moderate sedation or MAC","Systematic inspection: esophagus → GEJ → stomach (retroflex in fundus) → pylorus → duodenum","Therapeutic: biopsy, hemostasis (clips/cautery/injection/banding), dilation, FB removal, PEG"],pearls:"GI bleed timing: 12h if hemodynamically significant, 24h if stable. Glasgow-Blatchford 0-1: outpatient EGD. Erythromycin pre-EGD improves gastric visualization. Variceal bleeding: band ligation preferred. Esophageal dilation: Savary/balloon for strictures (max 3 dilations per session 'rule of 3')."},
  "Colonoscopy":{indication:"CRC screening (age 45+), lower GI bleeding, iron deficiency anemia, IBD surveillance, abnormal imaging, polypectomy",sites:["Transanal: rectum → sigmoid → descending → transverse → ascending → cecum ± terminal ileum"],steps:["Split-dose PEG bowel prep (half PM, half AM)","Moderate sedation or MAC","Advance to cecum (appendiceal orifice, tri-radiate fold, ileocecal valve)","≥6-min withdrawal time for adequate inspection","Polypectomy: cold/hot snare for polyps; EMR for larger flat lesions"],pearls:"CRC screening: age 45 (ACS) or 50 (USPSTF), q10yr if normal. Surveillance: tubular adenoma<10mm→7-10yr; advanced adenoma→3yr; IBD→q1-3yr after 8yr disease. EMR (endoscopic mucosal resection) for large polyps. ESD (endoscopic submucosal dissection) for early neoplasia. Complications: perforation 0.01-0.3%, post-polypectomy bleeding 0.3-1%."},
  "ERCP (Endoscopic Retrograde Cholangiopancreatography)":{indication:"Choledocholithiasis (bile duct stones), biliary obstruction (malignant/benign), cholangitis, pancreatic duct evaluation, sphincter of Oddi dysfunction",sites:["Duodenoscope → major papilla → biliary/pancreatic duct cannulation"],steps:["Side-viewing duodenoscope to ampulla of Vater","Selective cannulation of bile duct or pancreatic duct","Fluoroscopic cholangiogram/pancreatogram","Therapeutic: sphincterotomy, stone extraction (balloon/basket), stent placement (plastic or metal)","Post-procedure: monitor for pancreatitis (most common complication)"],pearls:"Indications are almost exclusively THERAPEUTIC (MRCP for diagnosis). Sphincterotomy: facilitates stone extraction and stent placement. Post-ERCP pancreatitis: most common complication (3-10%), reduced with rectal indomethacin and pancreatic duct stenting. Biliary stents: plastic (temporary, exchanged q3mo) vs metal (permanent, malignant obstruction)."},
  "EUS (Endoscopic Ultrasound)":{indication:"Pancreatic mass/cyst evaluation+FNA, mediastinal/submucosal lesion biopsy, bile duct stone evaluation, locoregional staging (esophageal/pancreatic/rectal CA), drainage (pseudocyst, abscess, gallbladder)",sites:["Transesophageal or transgastric approach"],steps:["Echoendoscope with US transducer at tip","High-resolution imaging of GI wall layers and adjacent structures","FNA/FNB of lesions under real-time US guidance","EUS-guided drainage: transgastric/transduodenal placement of stent for fluid collections"],pearls:"EUS-FNA: >90% sensitivity for pancreatic masses. EUS-guided drainage replaces surgical drainage for many pancreatic pseudocysts and walled-off necrosis. Superior to CT for small pancreatic lesions and LN staging."},
  "Paracentesis":{indication:"New-onset ascites (diagnostic), suspicion for SBP (fever, abdominal pain, encephalopathy in cirrhosis), tense/symptomatic ascites (therapeutic)",sites:["LLQ preferred (2cm medial and 2cm superior to ASIS)","RLQ alternative (avoid cecum/appendix)","Midline infraumbilical (linea alba — avascular)"],steps:["Position patient supine or slight lateral decubitus (fluid shifts to dependent side)","Ultrasound to confirm fluid pocket ≥3cm depth AND identify bowel/vessels — mark site","Sterile prep and drape; apply sterile US probe cover if using real-time guidance","Local anesthesia: lidocaine wheal at skin, then infiltrate tract down to peritoneum (aspirate as you advance — flash of ascitic fluid confirms entry)","Insert paracentesis needle/catheter (typically 18G or 6 Fr catheter over needle) using Z-track technique (pull skin 2cm caudally before entering to create offset tract — prevents leak)","Advance while aspirating until free-flowing ascitic fluid obtained","For diagnostic tap: collect 50-60mL into tubes — send cell count with differential, albumin, total protein, gram stain, culture (inoculate blood culture bottles at bedside)","For therapeutic (large volume): connect catheter to vacuum bottles or drainage bag; remove up to 5-8L per session","If >5L removed: administer 25% albumin 6-8g per liter removed (e.g., 50g albumin for 8L) to prevent post-paracentesis circulatory dysfunction","Remove catheter, apply sterile dressing; keep patient in lateral position (puncture site up) to minimize leaking"],pearls:"Do NOT correct INR/platelets in cirrhosis — coagulopathy of liver disease is rebalanced and does not increase paracentesis bleeding risk (AASLD guidelines). SBP diagnosis: ascitic fluid PMN ≥250 cells/mm³ — start empiric cefotaxime or ceftriaxone immediately, do not wait for culture. SAAG (serum-ascites albumin gradient) ≥1.1 g/dL = portal hypertension. Culture sensitivity increases from ~50% to ~80% when ascitic fluid is inoculated into blood culture bottles at bedside. Albumin replacement after large-volume paracentesis reduces renal impairment and mortality. Complications rare (<1%): persistent leak (most common), bowel perforation, hemorrhage (inferior epigastric artery — avoid by staying lateral to rectus). Serial therapeutic paracentesis q2 weeks is reasonable for diuretic-refractory ascites. Consider TIPS referral if requiring frequent paracentesis.",usTip:"Probe: curvilinear (preferred) or phased array. Scan the LLQ with patient supine — identify a pocket of free fluid (anechoic) that is ≥3cm deep with no intervening bowel loops. Use color Doppler to identify and avoid the inferior epigastric artery (runs along lateral border of rectus). Mark the optimal pocket. Real-time US guidance is recommended over blind/landmark-based technique and has been shown to reduce complications. SHM position statement endorses US for all paracenteses."},
  "PEG Tube Placement":{indication:"Long-term enteral feeding (>4 weeks anticipated need), decompression in malignant bowel obstruction",sites:["Anterior gastric wall (transillumination-guided)"],steps:["EGD to identify optimal site via transillumination (light visible on anterior abdominal wall)","Local anesthesia, small abdominal incision","Needle insertion into stomach under endoscopic visualization","Pull-through technique: guidewire → PEG tube pulled through mouth into stomach and out abdominal wall","Bumper secured internally, external fixation device applied","NPO 4-6h post-procedure, then start feeds per protocol"],pearls:"Contraindications: coagulopathy, ascites, interposed organ (colon), peritoneal dialysis, prior gastrectomy. Complications: peristomal infection (most common, 5-15%), buried bumper, peritonitis, aspiration. Replace with low-profile button after tract matures (6-8 weeks). If tube accidentally removed <6 weeks: emergent replacement needed (tract closes rapidly)."},
  "Duodenal Stent Placement":{indication:"Malignant gastric outlet obstruction (GOO) — pancreatic head cancer, duodenal cancer, gastric cancer with pyloric/duodenal involvement; palliative relief of nausea/vomiting and inability to tolerate oral intake in patients with limited life expectancy or poor surgical candidates",sites:["Duodenum (D1-D2 junction most common)","Pylorus","Proximal jejunum (post-ligament of Treitz occasionally)"],steps:["Pre-procedure imaging (CT abdomen) to define stricture location, length, and degree of obstruction","EGD to visualize stricture; assess length and morphology endoscopically","Pass guidewire across stricture under fluoroscopic and/or endoscopic guidance","If unable to traverse with standard endoscope, may use pediatric scope or balloon-assisted enteroscopy","Deploy self-expanding metal stent (SEMS) — uncovered preferred for malignant GOO (lower migration rate)","Stent must extend ≥2cm beyond stricture margins on both ends","Confirm adequate expansion and position with fluoroscopy and endoscopic visualization","Post-procedure: liquid diet day 1, advance to soft/low-residue diet over 24-48h as tolerated"],pearls:"Duodenal SEMS vs surgical gastrojejunostomy: stent offers faster symptom relief and shorter hospital stay, but surgical bypass has better long-term patency and fewer reinterventions — choose based on life expectancy (stent if <3-6 months, surgery if longer expected survival). Uncovered SEMS preferred over covered for duodenal GOO (covered stents have higher migration rates ~20% vs ~5%). Technical success >95%, clinical success (ability to tolerate oral intake) ~85-90%. Stent occlusion (tumor ingrowth/overgrowth): can restent or place stent-in-stent. Biliary obstruction coexisting: may need ERCP with biliary stent BEFORE or concurrent with duodenal stent (duodenal stent can block ampulla access). Avoid in patients with perforation, peritonitis, or multi-level obstruction. GOO scoring: 0=no oral intake, 1=liquids only, 2=soft solids, 3=full diet — goal is improvement by ≥1 level."}
},
"Nephrology":{
  "Hemodialysis Catheter Placement":{indication:"Emergent hemodialysis or CRRT when no permanent vascular access exists, plasmapheresis, acute indications for dialysis (AEIOU: Acidosis, Electrolytes, Intoxication, Overload, Uremia)",sites:["Right internal jugular vein (STRONGLY preferred — straight path to SVC/RA, lowest stenosis risk)","Femoral vein (temporary only — high infection risk, patient must remain supine)","AVOID subclavian vein (high rate of central vein stenosis that can permanently compromise future AV fistula creation on that side)"],steps:["Position patient supine with head turned slightly to the contralateral side (IJ) or supine with leg externally rotated (femoral)","Ultrasound to identify the target vein, confirm patency, and rule out thrombus — use real-time US guidance throughout (mandatory per guidelines)","Sterile prep and drape widely; apply sterile US probe cover","Infiltrate local anesthesia (lidocaine 1%) at the skin entry site and along the anticipated needle tract","Using Seldinger technique under real-time US guidance: insert the access needle into the vein, confirm venous blood return (dark, non-pulsatile), and advance the guidewire through the needle","Confirm wire position: the wire should advance freely without resistance; use fluoroscopy or US to verify wire is in the venous system (not arterial)","Make a small skin incision at the wire entry site; advance the dilator over the wire to create a tract, then remove the dilator","For non-tunneled catheters: advance the dual-lumen dialysis catheter over the wire to the appropriate depth (R IJ: ~15 cm to SVC/RA junction; femoral: ~20-25 cm)","Remove the wire, aspirate and flush both lumens with heparinized saline, clamp ports","Secure the catheter with sutures and apply a sterile occlusive dressing","Obtain CXR to confirm tip position at the SVC/RA junction (for IJ placement) and rule out pneumothorax"],pearls:"ALWAYS right IJ as first choice — the AHA/KDOQI guidelines strongly recommend this site. NEVER use subclavian for dialysis access — central vein stenosis rates are 40-50% and can permanently ruin the ipsilateral arm for future AV fistula creation. Temporary (non-tunneled) catheters should be removed or exchanged within 2-3 weeks due to infection risk. For longer-term dialysis access (>2-3 weeks), place a tunneled catheter (Permcath) with a subcutaneous Dacron cuff that acts as a barrier to infection. Catheter-related bloodstream infection (CRBSI): generally REMOVE the catheter (do not exchange over wire for suspected infection) and place new catheter at a different site after blood cultures clear. Dialysis catheter flow rates: must be able to deliver 300-400 mL/min for adequate HD. Catheter dysfunction: thrombolytic lock (alteplase 2 mg per lumen) for sluggish flow."},
  "Kidney Biopsy":{indication:"Unexplained acute kidney injury (AKI), unexplained chronic kidney disease (CKD) with normal-sized kidneys, nephrotic syndrome (to determine histologic subtype and guide treatment), nephritic syndrome/rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis, lupus nephritis (ISN/RPS classification guides therapy), kidney transplant dysfunction (rule out rejection)",sites:["Left kidney lower pole (native biopsy — preferably the left to avoid the liver)","Transplant kidney (iliac fossa — superficial location, easier access)"],steps:["Review pre-procedure labs: check platelet count (>50,000), INR (<1.5), PTT, bleeding time; hold anticoagulation and antiplatelet agents per protocol; check blood pressure (must be <140/90 before proceeding)","Obtain informed consent discussing risks: bleeding (most common), pain, AV fistula, need for transfusion, rare nephrectomy","Position patient prone with a bolster/rolled towel under the abdomen to push the kidney posteriorly (native); supine for transplant kidney","Ultrasound to identify the kidney, measure depth from skin to lower pole cortex, identify the lower pole target site, and confirm both kidneys are present","Sterile prep and drape; infiltrate generous local anesthesia (lidocaine 1%) from skin through the renal capsule along the planned biopsy trajectory","Under real-time US guidance, advance the biopsy needle (typically 16G automated spring-loaded biopsy gun) to the renal capsule, confirm position, and ask the patient to hold their breath","Fire the biopsy device and immediately withdraw — the needle captures a core of tissue (should be 1-2 cm length)","Inspect the core: confirm cortical tissue is present (glomeruli needed — medullary tissue alone is non-diagnostic). Typically obtain 2-3 cores for adequate sampling","Apply direct pressure to the biopsy site for 10-15 minutes after needle removal","Post-procedure monitoring: strict bed rest for 6-8 hours (lying on the biopsied side to apply pressure), serial vitals q15 min × 1 hour then q30 min × 2 hours, check post-procedure hemoglobin at 6-8 hours, monitor for gross hematuria","Obtain post-procedure US if there is concern for bleeding (perinephric hematoma)"],pearls:"Adequate tissue is critical: minimum 7-10 glomeruli for light microscopy (LM), tissue for immunofluorescence (IF), and tissue for electron microscopy (EM). LM results return in 1-2 days, IF in 2-3 days, and EM takes 2-4 weeks. Dry tap or fragmented tissue may indicate severe fibrosis or amyloidosis. Contraindications: uncontrolled hypertension (treat first), uncorrectable bleeding diathesis, solitary functioning kidney (relative — may still biopsy if indication is strong), small echogenic kidneys (irreversible CKD — biopsy unlikely to change management), active UTI or pyelonephritis, uncooperative patient. Complications: perinephric hematoma (most common, usually self-limited), gross hematuria (5-7%), AV fistula (<1%, usually asymptomatic), transfusion needed (~1%), nephrectomy (<0.01%). In lupus nephritis, biopsy findings directly determine treatment: class III/IV requires immunosuppression, class V may require different agents, class I/II may be managed conservatively."}
},
"Hematology / Oncology":{
  "Bone Marrow Biopsy & Aspirate":{indication:"Unexplained cytopenias (anemia, thrombocytopenia, leukopenia, pancytopenia), suspected hematologic malignancy (leukemia, lymphoma staging, myeloma, myelodysplastic syndrome), evaluation of fever of unknown origin, staging of known malignancy, monitoring treatment response, unexplained splenomegaly, evaluation of iron stores",sites:["Posterior superior iliac spine (PSIS — strongly preferred, largest and safest marrow space)","Anterior iliac crest (if patient cannot be positioned prone — e.g., morbid obesity, pregnancy)","Sternum (rarely used, higher risk of perforation — reserved for specific situations)"],steps:["Position patient in lateral decubitus (fetal position) or prone; identify the PSIS by palpating the bony prominence of the posterior iliac crest","Sterile prep and drape widely over the iliac crest region","Infiltrate generous local anesthesia (lidocaine 1%) — create a skin wheal, then advance the needle to the periosteum, infiltrating generously AT the periosteum (this is where the pain is); allow 3-5 minutes for full anesthetic effect","For the ASPIRATE: insert the aspiration needle (Jamshidi or Illinois needle) through the skin incision, advance to the periosteum, then use firm rotational pressure to penetrate the outer cortex (a give or pop is felt upon entering the marrow cavity)","Remove the inner trocar, attach a 10-20 mL syringe, and aspirate with a single brisk pull — the patient will feel a deep, sharp pain (warn them); collect 1-2 mL for the first pull (best quality — least hemodiluted)","Prepare touch preparations (touch preps) immediately: touch the aspirate spicules to glass slides before placing in EDTA tube — these are critical if the aspirate is suboptimal","Additional aspirate pulls: obtain specimens for flow cytometry (EDTA tube), cytogenetics/FISH (sodium heparin tube), molecular studies, and iron stain as clinically indicated","For the CORE BIOPSY: using the same skin incision (or reinsert at a slightly different angle), advance the Jamshidi biopsy needle to the periosteum, penetrate the cortex with rotational pressure","Once in the marrow cavity, advance the needle 1-2 cm using a rocking/rotating motion to capture a core specimen, then rotate the needle 360° to detach the specimen and withdraw","Remove the specimen from the needle using the obturator pushed retrograde (narrow end first) — the core should be ≥1.5-2 cm in length for adequate assessment","Apply firm pressure with sterile gauze for 5-10 minutes; apply a pressure dressing and instruct patient to lie on their back for 30-60 minutes to maintain pressure on the site"],pearls:"Always obtain BOTH aspirate AND core biopsy — they provide complementary information (aspirate for cell morphology, flow cytometry, cytogenetics; core for architecture, cellularity, fibrosis). A dry tap (inability to aspirate marrow) suggests packed marrow (leukemia), fibrosis (myelofibrosis), or necrosis — the core biopsy is especially critical in this situation. Touch preps are essential when the aspirate is a dry tap or hemodiluted. Complications are rare (<0.1%): bleeding/hematoma (most common, usually self-limited), infection, needle breakage, retroperitoneal hemorrhage (extremely rare). Patients on anticoagulation: hold warfarin/DOACs per protocol, but the procedure can often be performed safely with appropriate management. Pain management: adequate periosteal anesthesia is the single most important factor — many providers also offer anxiolysis with oral lorazepam or IV midazolam. Pediatric patients typically require procedural sedation. The specimen processing order matters: touch preps first (before EDTA), then aspirate smears, then tubes for flow/cytogenetics/molecular."},
  "Intrathecal Chemotherapy (via LP)":{indication:"CNS prophylaxis/treatment in ALL, CNS lymphoma, leptomeningeal carcinomatosis",sites:["L3-L4 or L4-L5 interspace (standard LP)"],steps:["Standard LP technique","After opening pressure measured, inject intrathecal chemotherapy (methotrexate 12mg, cytarabine 50-100mg, or rituximab)","Liposomal cytarabine (DepoCyt): sustained release, given less frequently"],pearls:"Preserve sterility — intrathecal medications are neurotoxic if contaminated. Ommaya reservoir: surgically placed subcutaneous port for repeated intrathecal access (avoids repeated LPs). Post-LP headache may be more common with repeated procedures."},
  "Central Venous Port Placement":{indication:"Long-term IV chemotherapy, frequent blood draws, poor peripheral access",sites:["Subclavian or IJ access → port chamber in subcutaneous chest pocket"],steps:["Typically placed by surgery or IR under fluoroscopy","Tunneled catheter connected to subcutaneous port","Access with Huber needle through skin into port septum","Flush with heparin after each use"],pearls:"Lower infection rate than PICC or tunneled catheter for long-term use. Can remain in place for years. Port-a-cath infections: may attempt antibiotic lock therapy before removal (unlike temporary catheters). Must use Huber needle (coring needles damage the septum)."},
  "Apheresis / Leukapheresis / Stem Cell Collection":{indication:"Apheresis: TTP (plasma exchange), myasthenia crisis. Leukapheresis: hyperleukocytosis (WBC>100K). Stem cell collection: pre-transplant",sites:["Via large-bore dialysis-type catheter or peripheral apheresis catheter"],steps:["Dual-lumen vascular access","Blood circulated through apheresis machine","Targeted component removed (plasma, WBCs, or stem cells)","Remaining components returned to patient"],pearls:"TTP: plasma exchange is EMERGENT — reduces mortality from >90% to <20%. Exchange 1-1.5 plasma volumes with FFP replacement. Leukapheresis: temporizing in symptomatic hyperleukocytosis (leukostasis) before chemotherapy. Stem cell mobilization: G-CSF ± plerixafor → collect peripheral blood stem cells."}
},
"Rheumatology":{
  "Arthrocentesis & Joint/Bursa/Tendon Sheath Injections":{indication:"Diagnostic arthrocentesis: see General IM section. Therapeutic injections: inflammatory arthritis flare (RA, psoriatic, crystalline), bursitis (olecranon, trochanteric, subacromial, prepatellar, pes anserine), tendinopathy (lateral epicondylitis, de Quervain), trigger finger (stenosing tenosynovitis), carpal tunnel syndrome",sites:["Joints: knee, shoulder, ankle, wrist, MCP, PIP, hip (US-guided for deep joints)","Bursae: olecranon, trochanteric (greater trochanteric pain syndrome), subacromial, prepatellar, pes anserine","Tendon sheaths: flexor tendons (trigger finger — A1 pulley), first dorsal compartment (de Quervain)"],steps:["Identify the target structure using anatomical landmarks and/or ultrasound guidance — US is strongly recommended for deep structures (hip, shoulder glenohumeral, small joints) and improves accuracy for all injections","Sterile prep of the injection site; apply ethyl chloride spray or infiltrate local anesthetic (lidocaine 1%) at the skin entry point","For JOINT injections: insert the needle into the joint space, aspirate to confirm intra-articular position (synovial fluid return), then inject the corticosteroid-anesthetic mixture","For BURSAL injections: insert the needle into the bursa (identify as a fluid-filled structure on US), aspirate any effusion for analysis if diagnostic concern (septic bursitis), then inject","For TENDON SHEATH injections (trigger finger): insert the needle at the level of the A1 pulley (MCP joint flexion crease), advance into the tendon sheath (NOT into the tendon itself — feel for loss of resistance), confirm sheath position by asking patient to flex/extend the finger (needle should move with the tendon, not be fixed in it)","Injection mixture: corticosteroid (triamcinolone acetonide 40 mg for large joints, 20 mg for medium joints, 5-10 mg for small joints/tendons) mixed with local anesthetic (1-3 mL lidocaine 1% or bupivacaine 0.25%)","Post-injection: remove needle, apply bandage, advise patient to rest the joint for 24-48 hours and monitor for signs of infection"],pearls:"Maximum 3-4 corticosteroid injections per joint per year due to concerns about cartilage damage, tendon weakening, and systemic effects. Steroid flare: transient worsening of pain 24-48 hours post-injection occurs in ~5% of patients (crystal-induced synovitis from steroid crystite) — ice and NSAIDs for management. Post-injection hyperglycemia in diabetic patients: blood glucose can rise significantly for 2-5 days — warn patients and adjust insulin accordingly. Tendon injection precaution: NEVER inject directly INTO the tendon substance (risk of tendon rupture) — always inject around or alongside the tendon (peritendinous). Absolute contraindications: suspected septic joint or overlying cellulitis/skin infection, prosthetic joint injection without orthopedic guidance, bacteremia. Evidence for efficacy: joint injections provide 4-8 weeks of relief in OA/inflammatory arthritis, subacromial injections have modest short-term benefit, trigger finger injections have ~60-70% cure rate after 1-2 injections. US guidance improves injection accuracy from ~60% (blind) to >95% for most targets."},
  "Temporal Artery Biopsy":{indication:"Suspected giant cell arteritis (GCA) — usually performed by surgery",sites:["Temporal artery (superficial temporal artery branch)"],steps:["Local anesthesia along temporal artery course","2-3cm incision over artery","Identify and isolate artery","Excise ≥2cm segment (skip lesions — longer specimen ↑ sensitivity)","Close incision","Specimen to pathology (granulomatous inflammation, intimal hyperplasia, fragmented internal elastic lamina)"],pearls:"Do NOT delay steroids for biopsy — start immediately if clinical suspicion high. Biopsy within 1-2 weeks of starting steroids (still diagnostic). Negative biopsy does not exclude GCA (skip lesions — consider bilateral biopsy). US 'halo sign' or PET-CT increasingly used as non-invasive alternatives."}
},
"Endocrinology":{
  "Thyroid Fine Needle Aspiration (FNA)":{indication:"Thyroid nodule meeting biopsy criteria (Bethesda/TI-RADS), suspicious lymphadenopathy",sites:["Thyroid nodule (US-guided)"],steps:["Patient supine with neck extended","US identifies nodule and planned needle path","Sterile prep, local anesthesia optional","22-27G needle advanced into nodule under real-time US","Aspiration with multiple passes (capillary or suction technique)","Slides prepared and sent for cytology"],pearls:"Bethesda classification: I (non-diagnostic, repeat), II (benign), III (atypia of undetermined significance), IV (follicular neoplasm), V (suspicious for malignancy), VI (malignant). Molecular testing (Afirma, ThyroSeq) for Bethesda III-IV to avoid diagnostic surgery. Most FNAs performed by endocrinology, radiology, or surgery."},
  "Continuous Glucose Monitor (CGM) & Insulin Pump":{indication:"CGM: T1DM, insulin-requiring T2DM, gestational DM, hypoglycemia unawareness. Insulin pump: T1DM, select T2DM",sites:["CGM sensor: subcutaneous (arm, abdomen)","Insulin pump: subcutaneous infusion set (abdomen, thigh, arm)"],steps:["CGM: apply sensor subcutaneously, pair with receiver/phone","Calibrate per device requirements (some factory-calibrated)","Insulin pump: program basal rates, bolus calculator, insert infusion set","Closed-loop systems (hybrid AID): CGM + pump with automated insulin adjustments"],pearls:"CGM reduces A1c and hypoglycemia in T1DM. Time-in-range (TIR 70-180) is key CGM metric — goal >70%. Hybrid closed-loop (670G, Control-IQ, Omnipod 5): automated basal adjustment + some bolus. Patients still need carb counting and bolus dosing. Inpatient: generally transition to basal-bolus (remove pump) unless patient/endo can manage."}
},
"Neurology":{
  "Lumbar Puncture (LP)":{indication:"Diagnostic: suspected meningitis/encephalitis, subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH) with negative CT, normal pressure hydrocephalus (NPH) evaluation, CNS malignancy (leptomeningeal carcinomatosis), multiple sclerosis (oligoclonal bands), neurosarcoidosis, autoimmune encephalitis. Therapeutic: idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH) with symptomatic elevated ICP, therapeutic LP for large-volume CSF drainage",sites:["L3-L4 interspace (preferred — below the conus medullaris which typically ends at L1-L2)","L4-L5 interspace (alternative)","Identify the L4 spinous process at the level of the iliac crests (Tuffier's line)"],steps:["Review imaging: obtain CT head BEFORE LP if any of the following are present: immunocompromise, history of CNS disease, new-onset seizure, papilledema, altered consciousness, focal neurological deficit (to rule out mass lesion/elevated ICP that could cause herniation)","Position patient in lateral decubitus (fetal position) with knees drawn to chest and chin tucked, or seated upright leaning forward over a bedside table (opening pressure can only be measured accurately in lateral decubitus)","Identify the L3-L4 or L4-L5 interspace using Tuffier's line (imaginary line between iliac crests crosses at approximately L4). Ultrasound can significantly improve landmark identification, especially in obese patients","Sterile prep and drape; infiltrate local anesthetic (lidocaine 1%) subcutaneously and deeper along the intended needle trajectory into the interspinous ligament","Insert the spinal needle (20-22G atraumatic/Sprotte preferred over cutting-tip Quincke to reduce post-LP headache) with the bevel parallel to the longitudinal dural fibers (if using Quincke needle), directed slightly cephalad toward the umbilicus","Advance through the skin → subcutaneous tissue → supraspinous ligament → interspinous ligament → ligamentum flavum → dura (a pop or give is felt upon entering the dura/subarachnoid space)","Remove the stylet and observe for CSF flow; if no flow, rotate the needle 90° (bevel may be abutting a nerve root) or advance slightly","Measure OPENING PRESSURE with a manometer (normal: 6-20 cmH2O in lateral decubitus; patient must be relaxed with legs partially extended for accurate reading)","Collect CSF in sequential sterile tubes: Tube 1 — cell count and differential; Tube 2 — protein, glucose; Tube 3 — gram stain, bacterial culture, additional studies (viral PCR, fungal culture, cytology, oligoclonal bands, autoimmune panels as indicated); Tube 4 — cell count and differential (compare Tube 1 vs Tube 4 to distinguish traumatic tap from true SAH)","Typical volume: collect 1-2 mL per tube (8-10 mL total for diagnostic LP); for therapeutic LP in IIH, may remove 20-40 mL","Replace the stylet before withdrawing the needle (reduces risk of post-LP headache), apply sterile bandage"],pearls:"Post-LP headache (PDPH) occurs in ~10-30% of patients (less with atraumatic needles, ~5%): positional headache worse when upright, improved when supine. Management: bedside rest, caffeine (300-500 mg PO or IV), hydration; if persistent >24-48 hours, epidural blood patch (gold standard, >90% effective). Traumatic tap vs SAH: traumatic tap shows decreasing RBC count from Tube 1 to Tube 4, while SAH shows consistent RBC count across tubes; xanthochromia (yellow CSF from bilirubin breakdown) confirms SAH (appears >6-12 hours after bleed). Contraindications: significant coagulopathy (INR >1.5, platelets <50,000 — correct first), space-occupying lesion with mass effect on CT (risk of herniation), overlying skin infection. CSF interpretation: bacterial meningitis — high WBC (usually >1000, predominantly neutrophils), low glucose (<40 or CSF:serum ratio <0.4), high protein (>250 mg/dL); viral meningitis — moderate WBC (10-500, predominantly lymphocytes), normal glucose, mildly elevated protein. CT head sensitivity for SAH: ~98% within 6 hours, declining to ~90% at 12 hours and ~50% at 1 week — LP still needed for late presentations with negative CT.",usTip:"Probe: curvilinear (low-frequency, for depth) or linear (for thinner patients). Ultrasound significantly improves first-pass success in LP by identifying the midline, intervertebral space, and depth to the ligamentum flavum/dura. Scan in the transverse and longitudinal (sagittal) planes: in transverse, identify the spinous process shadows and the acoustic window between them; in sagittal (paramedian), visualize the laminae and identify interspaces. Mark the optimal interspace and planned needle trajectory. Especially valuable in obese patients, edematous patients, and those with difficult landmarks. SHM position statement recommends US-assisted LP."},
  "External Ventricular Drain (EVD) Management":{indication:"Acute obstructive hydrocephalus (cerebellar stroke, intraventricular hemorrhage, tumor), ICP monitoring and CSF drainage in traumatic brain injury or subarachnoid hemorrhage, CNS infection requiring intrathecal antibiotic administration, temporary CSF diversion before permanent shunt placement",sites:["Kocher's point: 11 cm posterior to the nasion (or 1 cm anterior to the coronal suture) AND 3 cm lateral to the midline (mid-pupillary line) — typically on the right (non-dominant) side"],steps:["EVD placement is performed by neurosurgery (typically at bedside in the ICU or in the OR) — a ventriculostomy catheter is advanced through a burr hole at Kocher's point into the frontal horn of the lateral ventricle, with the target being the ipsilateral foramen of Monro","After placement, the EVD is connected to a closed external drainage system with a graduated collection chamber, pressure transducer, and drip chamber","ZEROING the EVD: the zero reference point must be leveled to the tragus of the ear (approximates the foramen of Monro). Use a laser leveler to align the drip chamber stopcock with the tragus. Re-level with any patient repositioning","SET the drainage pressure: the height of the drip chamber above the zero point determines the ICP threshold at which CSF drains. Common settings: 10-20 cmH2O (set by neurosurgery order). A lower drainage height = more CSF drainage = lower ICP","MONITORING ICP: clamp the drain briefly and transduce the pressure to obtain an accurate ICP reading (ICP cannot be measured while the drain is open). Normal ICP: 5-15 mmHg. Treat sustained ICP >20-22 mmHg per Brain Trauma Foundation guidelines","Assess CSF output: document hourly CSF drainage volume and color. Normal CSF: clear and colorless. Bloody or cloudy CSF should be reported. Typical drainage: 5-20 mL/hour (varies with disease process)","Monitor for complications: overdrainage (sudden headache, collapse of ventricles on CT — raise drainage level), underdrainage/catheter occlusion (rising ICP — flush per neurosurgery protocol), infection (ventriculitis — daily CSF surveillance per institutional protocol), hemorrhage at insertion site"],pearls:"Never lower the EVD drainage height without a neurosurgery order — sudden overdrainage can cause upward herniation or subdural hematoma. Always CLAMP the EVD before moving the patient (repositioning, transport, sitting up) and re-level after repositioning — failure to re-level is a common and dangerous error. EVD-related ventriculitis occurs in ~5-10% of EVDs: suspect if increasing CSF WBC, decreasing CSF glucose, fever, or altered mental status — send CSF cultures and start empiric intrathecal/IV antibiotics per neurosurgery. Weaning protocol: gradually raise the drainage level (e.g., by 5 cmH2O increments) and clamp for trial periods while monitoring ICP — if ICP remains <20 mmHg with the drain clamped for 24-48 hours, consider removal or conversion to a permanent VP shunt."},
  "Intracranial Pressure (ICP) Monitoring":{indication:"Severe traumatic brain injury (GCS ≤8 with abnormal CT head), fulminant hepatic failure with cerebral edema, subarachnoid hemorrhage with hydrocephalus, large hemispheric stroke with concern for herniation, post-craniotomy monitoring, refractory elevated ICP of any cause",sites:["Intraventricular catheter/EVD (gold standard — allows both monitoring AND therapeutic CSF drainage, placed via Kocher's point)","Intraparenchymal bolt/microsensor (Codman, Camino — placed through a burr hole into brain parenchyma; monitors ICP but cannot drain CSF)"],steps:["ICP monitor placement is performed by neurosurgery — see EVD section for ventriculostomy technique; intraparenchymal bolts are placed through a small burr hole and advanced ~2 cm into brain parenchyma","After placement, connect to the monitoring system and zero the transducer","Continuous ICP monitoring: normal ICP is 5-15 mmHg. Treatment threshold: sustained ICP >20-22 mmHg (Brain Trauma Foundation guidelines)","Calculate cerebral perfusion pressure (CPP): CPP = MAP - ICP. Target CPP 60-70 mmHg (avoid CPP <60 which is associated with brain ischemia)","ICP waveform interpretation: normal waveform shows P1 (percussion wave) > P2 (tidal wave) > P3 (dicrotic wave). When P2 > P1, this suggests decreased intracranial compliance (warning sign of decompensation)","Stepwise ICP management (tiered approach): Tier 1 — head of bed 30°, midline head position, ensure adequate sedation/analgesia, treat fever/seizures, osmotherapy (mannitol 0.5-1 g/kg or hypertonic saline 23.4% 30 mL via central line). Tier 2 — deepen sedation (propofol or midazolam), optimize CPP with vasopressors, CSF drainage via EVD. Tier 3 — pentobarbital coma (last resort medical therapy), decompressive craniectomy (surgical)","Monitor for Cushing response (hypertension + bradycardia + irregular respirations) — a late and ominous sign of impending herniation requiring emergent intervention"],pearls:"The intraventricular catheter (EVD) is the gold standard because it allows simultaneous monitoring AND treatment (CSF drainage). Intraparenchymal monitors are simpler to place and have lower infection rates but cannot drain CSF and are prone to drift (loss of calibration over time — cannot be re-zeroed after placement). Plateau waves (Lundberg A waves): sustained ICP elevations to 50-100 mmHg lasting 5-20 minutes — indicate severely compromised intracranial compliance and risk of herniation, requiring immediate intervention. Herniation syndromes to recognize: uncal (CN III palsy, ipsilateral pupil dilation, contralateral hemiparesis), central (bilateral pupil fixation, decerebrate posturing), tonsillar (bradycardia, respiratory arrest). Mannitol vs hypertonic saline: both effective for acute ICP reduction; hypertonic saline may be preferred in hypotensive patients (mannitol causes diuresis and can worsen hypotension). Target sodium 145-155 mEq/L when using hypertonic saline."},
  "tPA Administration for Acute Ischemic Stroke":{indication:"Acute ischemic stroke with measurable neurological deficit, onset (or last known well) within 4.5 hours, no absolute contraindications to thrombolysis. Extended window: IV tenecteplase or endovascular thrombectomy may be considered up to 24 hours with favorable imaging",sites:["IV administration (peripheral IV, preferably in antecubital fossa)","Intra-arterial (endovascular thrombectomy — performed by neurointerventional radiology)"],steps:["ACTIVATE stroke code: immediate non-contrast CT head to rule out hemorrhage (must be completed and interpreted rapidly — target door-to-CT <25 minutes)","Perform rapid neurological assessment using NIHSS (National Institutes of Health Stroke Scale) to quantify deficit severity — document the score (ranges 0-42, higher = more severe)","Review absolute contraindications: intracranial hemorrhage on CT, prior ICH, known intracranial neoplasm/AVM, active internal bleeding, recent intracranial/spinal surgery (<3 months), severe uncontrolled hypertension (>185/110 despite treatment), platelet count <100,000, INR >1.7, aPTT elevated, blood glucose <50 mg/dL","If within 4.5-hour window with no contraindications: administer alteplase (tPA) 0.9 mg/kg IV (maximum 90 mg total) — give 10% of the total dose as an IV bolus over 1 minute, then infuse the remaining 90% over 60 minutes","Blood pressure management: MUST control BP to <185/110 BEFORE administering tPA (use IV labetalol 10-20 mg or nicardipine drip 5 mg/hr titrated). After tPA: maintain BP <180/105 for 24 hours","Establish neurochecks: perform focused neurological exam (NIHSS, pupil reactivity, level of consciousness) every 15 minutes during infusion, every 30 minutes for the next 6 hours, then hourly for 24 hours","Monitor for hemorrhagic transformation: if patient develops sudden headache, acute hypertension, nausea/vomiting, or neurological deterioration during or after infusion — STOP tPA immediately, obtain emergent CT head, check fibrinogen/CBC/PT, consider cryoprecipitate and tranexamic acid","NPO until swallowing assessment completed; avoid Foley catheter, arterial puncture, and NG tube insertion for 24 hours post-tPA","Obtain follow-up CT or MRI brain at 24 hours post-tPA before starting antiplatelet or anticoagulant therapy","For large vessel occlusion (LVO): evaluate for endovascular thrombectomy — indicated for anterior circulation LVO (ICA, M1 MCA) within 24 hours with salvageable tissue on perfusion imaging (DAWN/DEFUSE-3 trials)"],pearls:"Time is brain: every 15-minute delay in tPA administration is associated with measurably worse outcomes — target door-to-needle time <60 minutes. The 4.5-hour window has additional relative exclusion criteria (age >80, NIHSS >25, diabetes + prior stroke, oral anticoagulant use regardless of INR) per ECASS III, though these are increasingly individualized. Tenecteplase (0.25 mg/kg single IV bolus, max 25 mg) is emerging as a simpler alternative to alteplase with similar or superior efficacy for LVO strokes (AcT trial) — check institutional protocols. NIHSS score guides management: score 0-4 (minor stroke, consider non-treatment), 5-25 (moderate-severe, strong indication for thrombolysis), >25 (severe, still treat but higher hemorrhage risk). Endovascular thrombectomy: for LVO strokes, thrombectomy has a number needed to treat (NNT) of ~3-4, making it one of the most effective interventions in medicine — do NOT delay thrombectomy to complete IV tPA infusion (bridging approach: give tPA bolus then transfer to angiography suite). Stroke mimics (seizure, migraine, conversion disorder, hypoglycemia) account for ~15-25% of stroke codes — tPA given to mimics has very low complication rates, so do not delay treatment due to diagnostic uncertainty. Post-tPA hemorrhage rate: ~6% symptomatic ICH."}
},
"POCUS (Point-of-Care Ultrasound)":{
  "Ultrasound Fundamentals & Knobology":{indication:"Foundation knowledge required before performing any US-guided procedure or diagnostic POCUS exam",sites:["N/A — conceptual framework applicable to all US applications"],steps:["Select the correct probe for the clinical question: LINEAR (high-frequency 5-15 MHz) for superficial structures (vessels, nerves, soft tissue, pneumothorax, procedures within 4-6cm depth); PHASED ARRAY (low-frequency 1-5 MHz) for cardiac and deep thoracic/abdominal views through narrow acoustic windows (ribs); CURVILINEAR (low-frequency 2-5 MHz) for deep abdominal structures, FAST, aorta, renal, and OB","Adjust DEPTH to place the target structure in the center of the screen — too deep wastes resolution, too shallow may miss pathology","Adjust GAIN to optimize image brightness — overall gain affects entire image; TGC (time-gain compensation) adjusts brightness at specific depths to compensate for attenuation","Select the correct EXAM PRESET on the machine (cardiac, vascular, abdominal, MSK) — this auto-optimizes frequency, gain curves, and post-processing","Orient the PROBE INDICATOR to the patient's right (transverse) or head (longitudinal) — correlates with the screen marker (typically upper-left dot)","Use 2D (B-mode) as default imaging mode; switch to M-MODE for motion over time at a single line (cardiac valve motion, lung sliding, IVC respiratory variation); switch to COLOR DOPPLER to assess blood flow direction and presence","Apply adequate GEL — poor coupling = poor image. Use sterile gel and probe covers for procedures","SAVE images and clips per institutional protocol — documentation of POCUS findings is a medicolegal expectation"],pearls:"Key physics concept: higher frequency = better resolution but less penetration depth (linear probe); lower frequency = deeper penetration but lower resolution (curvilinear/phased array). Common artifacts to recognize: acoustic shadowing (behind bone/calcification — loss of signal), posterior acoustic enhancement (behind fluid — brighter signal), reverberation (A-lines in normal lung), mirror artifact (near diaphragm). Clean probes between patients per infection control guidelines — low-level disinfection for intact skin, high-level disinfection for mucous membrane or sterile procedures. POCUS is an extension of the physical exam, not a replacement for formal diagnostic ultrasound. For a deeper dive into US physics, probe selection, and image optimization, see the Proceduralist.org Ultrasound Fundamentals curriculum (proceduralist.org/introduction/ultrasound-physics/).",resources:["https://proceduralist.org/introduction/ultrasound-physics/|Proceduralist.org — Ultrasound Fundamentals","https://proceduralist.org/introduction/|Proceduralist.org — Introduction to POCUS","https://vimeo.com/68189283|Alan Chiem's Introduction to Ultrasound (video)"]},
  "Focused Cardiac Ultrasound":{indication:"Hemodynamic assessment in shock, pericardial effusion, RV/LV function, volume status",sites:["Parasternal long axis, parasternal short axis, apical 4-chamber, subcostal, IVC"],steps:["Phased array (cardiac) probe","Parasternal long axis: assess LV size/function, pericardial effusion, valve motion, aortic root","Parasternal short axis: assess wall motion at papillary muscle level, D-sign (RV pressure/volume overload flattening the septum)","Apical 4-chamber: compare RV and LV size (RV:LV ratio >1:1 suggests RV dilation), assess TAPSE for RV systolic function","Subcostal: best view for pericardial effusion detection, IVC diameter and respiratory variation for volume status assessment"],pearls:"IVC collapsibility: >50% with sniff → low CVP (fluid responsive); <50% → elevated CVP. RUSH exam for undifferentiated shock: pump (cardiac), tank (IVC, lungs, FAST), pipes (aorta, DVT). TAPSE (tricuspid annular plane systolic excursion) <17mm suggests RV dysfunction. Cannot replace formal TTE — screens for gross pathology.",resources:["https://proceduralist.org/cardiovascular-ultrasound/cardiac-ultrasound/|Proceduralist.org — Cardiac Ultrasound","https://proceduralist.org/cardiovascular-ultrasound/intravascular-volume-status/|Proceduralist.org — Volume Status Assessment"]},
  "Lung Ultrasound":{indication:"Dyspnea, pneumothorax evaluation, pleural effusion, B-lines (pulmonary edema), consolidation",sites:["Anterior, lateral, posterior chest (6-8 zones bilaterally)"],steps:["Linear probe (pneumothorax) or curvilinear (effusion/parenchyma)","Identify pleural line, lung sliding, A-lines (normal), B-lines (pathologic)","Absent lung sliding + absent B-lines + barcode sign = pneumothorax","≥3 B-lines per zone = interstitial syndrome (pulmonary edema, fibrosis)","Consolidation: tissue-like appearance, air bronchograms"],pearls:"Lung US more sensitive than CXR for pneumothorax, pleural effusion, and pulmonary edema. BLUE protocol for acute dyspnea. B-lines: bilateral diffuse = cardiogenic pulmonary edema; unilateral/focal = pneumonia, contusion. Lung point: transition zone between normal lung sliding and absent sliding — confirms pneumothorax location.",resources:["https://proceduralist.org/pulmonary/lung-ultrasound/|Proceduralist.org — Lung Ultrasound"]},
  "FAST Exam & DVT Ultrasound":{indication:"FAST: trauma (free fluid). DVT US: suspected DVT",sites:["FAST: RUQ (Morrison's), LUQ (splenorenal), pelvis (suprapubic), subxiphoid. DVT: common femoral, superficial femoral, popliteal veins"],steps:["FAST: curvilinear probe, systematic 4 views, look for free fluid (anechoic stripes)","DVT: linear probe, compression at 2cm intervals from CFV to popliteal","Non-compressible vein = DVT (>90% sensitivity for proximal DVT)","Augmentation: squeeze calf, watch for flow in femoral vein"],pearls:"E-FAST adds thoracic views for hemothorax/pneumothorax. FAST sensitivity ~85% for free fluid (lower for solid organ injury — CT still gold standard). 2-point compression DVT (CFV + popliteal) has 97% sensitivity for proximal DVT. Full leg US adds calf veins (controversial clinical significance of isolated calf DVT).",resources:["https://proceduralist.org/abdomen/fast-exam-and-ascites/|Proceduralist.org — FAST Exam & Ascites","https://proceduralist.org/cardiovascular-ultrasound/deep-vein-thrombosis/|Proceduralist.org — DVT Ultrasound"]}
},
"Emergency / Cross-Cutting":{
  "Needle Decompression & Intraosseous Access":{indication:"Needle decomp: tension pneumothorax. IO: emergent vascular access when IV fails in <90 sec",sites:["Needle: 2nd ICS MCL or 5th ICS AAL. IO: proximal tibia, humeral head"],steps:["See previous detailed entries"],pearls:"See previous entries. 5th ICS AAL may be more reliable (chest wall thickness). IO: any medication/fluid can be given. Lidocaine flush 40mg for conscious patients. Remove IO within 24h."},
  "Incision & Drainage (I&D)":{indication:"Fluctuant abscess, perianal abscess, Bartholin abscess",sites:["Over maximal fluctuance"],steps:["See previous detailed entry"],pearls:"Antibiotics alone do NOT treat undrained abscess. Add antibiotics only if: cellulitis, systemic illness, immunocompromised. Loop drainage: vessel loop through 2 stab incisions — less painful."},
  "Skin Biopsy & Cryotherapy":{indication:"Skin biopsy: diagnosis of rash, suspected malignancy, vasculitis. Cryotherapy: warts, actinic keratoses, small benign lesions",sites:["Punch biopsy: lesion border (include normal+abnormal skin). Shave biopsy: raised/superficial lesions"],steps:["Punch: local anesthesia → 3-4mm punch tool → rotational pressure through dermis → remove specimen → close with suture","Shave: local anesthesia → razor blade or dermablade tangential to skin → hemostasis with aluminum chloride","Cryotherapy: liquid nitrogen applied with spray/probe → 5-10 sec freeze → thaw → repeat for aggressive lesions"],pearls:"Punch biopsy preferred for inflammatory conditions (gets deeper tissue). Shave for superficial/raised lesions (no suture needed). Avoid shave biopsy if melanoma suspected (need depth for staging). Elliptical excisional biopsy for suspicious melanocytic lesions."}
}
};
